## What Is a Pear Cut Diamond? The Complete Definition

A pear cut diamond — also called a pear shaped diamond, pear shape diamond, or teardrop diamond — is a modified brilliant-cut diamond with one rounded end and one pointed end, carrying 58 facets arranged to maximize brilliance across an asymmetrical outline. GIA classifies it as a fancy shape, meaning no official cut grade is issued — the same rule that applies to oval, marquise, and cushion cuts.

As a pear brilliant cut diamond — or pear brilliant diamond, as it is sometimes called — it shares the round brilliant's core facet architecture — 33 crown facets and 24 pavilion facets — adapted around an asymmetrical, elongated outline. This makes the diamond pear cut one of the brightest fancy shapes: it throws genuine scintillation across its surface, not just from the rounded end but across the full pear diamond shape.

The pear cut emerged in the 15th century, credited to Flemish polisher Lodewyk van Berquem, who is also credited with developing symmetrical faceting techniques that influenced nearly every modern diamond shape that followed. It is one of the oldest fancy shapes still in mainstream production today.

I'm **Farzana Hasan**, a GIA Expert. Pear cut diamonds occupy an interesting position in the 2026 market: demand is steady rather than surging like oval, but the buyers who choose pear tend to be deliberate about it — they want the elongating effect, the vintage-meets-modern versatility, and they're usually comfortable with the extra diligence the shape requires.

This guide covers the bow-tie physics specific to pear, the L/W ratio that determines how "classic" or "elongated" the shape reads, the setting requirements that protect the point, complete live price data from Blue Nile, and the lab-grown arbitrage that makes pear one of the more accessible fancy shapes right now.

Full credentials at **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**.

