## The Bow-Tie Effect in Pear Cut Diamonds

Every pear cut diamond has a bow-tie effect, the same as oval and marquise cuts. The bow-tie is a dark, shadowed band that appears across the widest section of the stone — roughly where the rounded curve transitions toward the body of the diamond — caused by the elongated facet pattern failing to reflect light back to the viewer from certain angles.

In a pear, the bow-tie typically sits in the broader, rounded portion of the stone rather than near the point, since that is where the elongated facet geometry is most pronounced.

The severity ranges from essentially invisible to a dominant dark shadow that makes the stone look lifeless regardless of how high its clarity and color grades are.

### How to Evaluate Bow-Tie Severity Before Buying a Pear

A GIA certificate contains no bow-tie assessment, and product photography can hide a severe bow-tie by shooting from an angle that minimizes the dark zone. The only reliable evaluation method is watching the 360° HD video of the specific stone you intend to buy.

The audit process: open the video on the retailer's product page, watch the stone rotate through at least two full rotations, and observe the broader rounded section as the stone faces directly up.

A minimal bow-tie reads as a subtle shadow that doesn't disrupt the overall brilliance. A severe bow-tie reads as a distinct, sharply defined dark shape that is visible without zooming in — reject these regardless of how attractive the certificate numbers look.

Proportions correlate with bow-tie severity here just as they do in oval: stones with excessive depth or poor L/W balance tend to show worse bow-ties. The proportion table below gives you the ranges that minimize the risk, but video confirmation is still mandatory.

