## What Is the Point Vulnerability in Pear Cut Diamonds — and How Do You Protect It?

This is the characteristic that genuinely separates pear from every other popular diamond shape: the point.

The tip of a pear cut diamond is the thinnest, most exposed section of the stone. Unlike a round, oval, or cushion — which have no sharp corners — a pear's point can chip if it strikes a hard surface at the wrong angle.

This is not a theoretical risk; it is a documented, well-known durability consideration in the jewelry trade, and it is the single most important setting decision a pear buyer makes.

**The fix is a V-prong (or V-tip) setting.** A V-prong is a single prong bent into a V-shape that wraps around and protects the point from both sides, distributing impact force away from the thinnest part of the stone.

A pear set without a V-prong — for example, in a simple 4-prong setting with a standard prong placed near the tip — is at meaningfully higher risk of point damage over years of daily wear.

**Before buying any pear setting, confirm:** the prong at the point is a V-prong specifically, not a standard rounded prong. Reputable retailers list this in the setting description. If it isn't specified, ask before purchasing — this is not a cosmetic detail, it is a structural one.

![Pear cut diamond V-prong mandate infographic — side-by-side comparison of a standard prong at the point vs a V-prong wrapping the tip, with chip risk zone highlighted](/images/pear-cut-diamond-v-prong-mandate.avif)

*The V-prong is not optional — it is the single setting detail that determines whether your pear's point is protected for decades or vulnerable from day one. **[Shop pear solitaire settings with V-prong on Blue Nile →](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring?shape=pear&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)***

## What Are the Ideal Proportions for a Pear Cut Diamond?

GIA does not issue a cut grade for pear cut diamonds. Every proportion must be verified manually from the certificate — this is the buyer's responsibility on every pear purchase, exactly as it is for oval, cushion, and every other fancy shape.

### Pear Cut Ideal Proportion Table ()

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Proportion</th><th>Ideal Range</th><th>Acceptable Range</th><th>Avoid</th><th>Farzana's Verdict</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Length-to-Width (L/W) Ratio</strong></td><td>1.50–1.65</td><td>1.45–1.75</td><td>Under 1.40 or over 1.80</td><td><strong>9/10 — The Single Most Important Number.</strong> This ratio determines whether the pear reads as a classic, balanced teardrop or an awkward, stubby outline. Below 1.40 looks rounded and unintentional; above 1.80 looks needle-thin and exaggerates bow-tie risk.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Table %</strong></td><td>53–63%</td><td>50–66%</td><td>Under 48% or over 70%</td><td><strong>8/10 — The Light Gateway.</strong> Same logic as oval: too high flattens the stone's brilliance, too low chokes light entry and makes the diamond look smaller and dimmer than its actual carat weight.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Depth %</strong></td><td>58–64%</td><td>56–68%</td><td>Under 54% or over 70%</td><td><strong>9/10 — The Bow-Tie and Brilliance Lever.</strong> Excess depth concentrates light loss out the sides and worsens bow-tie severity. Shallow stones lose brilliance and can look glassy or "fisheye."</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetry of the Point</strong></td><td>Centered, sharp but not razor-thin</td><td>Slightly off-center acceptable</td><td>Visibly crooked or bulbous point</td><td><strong>7/10 — Easy to Overlook, Hard to Unsee.</strong> A crooked point throws off the entire visual balance of the stone. Always check the point alignment on the video before purchasing — this detail rarely shows up in written specs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Wing Symmetry</strong></td><td>Even, no visible bulge on either side</td><td>Minor asymmetry under magnification only</td><td>Visible bulge or "belly" on one side</td><td><strong>8/10 — The Hidden Defect.</strong> Pear cuts are graded by GIA without an official symmetry score for fancy shapes, so an uneven "wing" (the curved sides) is something only a video or in-hand inspection will reveal.</td></tr></tbody></table>

