This is where the pear lab-grown market gets genuinely remarkable. Look at the cluster: roughly 15 separate IGI-certified 1.50ct D-IF Ideal cut pear lab diamonds, all priced at exactly **$3,380**.

This kind of price clustering tells you the lab diamond market has standardized pricing at this specific grade combination — it isn't one retailer's pricing quirk, it's the market finding equilibrium.

Compare that **$3,380** lab D-IF at 1.50ct to the natural 1ct D-VS1 at **[$3,810](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29112328?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)** above — the lab stone is half a carat larger, a full clarity grade better (IF vs VS1), and still costs less. That is the **Lab-Grown Arbitrage** in its clearest form: more diamond, better grade, lower price.

One more data point worth flagging: E-IF lab pears at 1.50–1.61ct run **$3,060–$3,280**, consistently cheaper than the D-IF cluster at **$3,380**.

The color premium for D over E in lab-grown pear is real but small — roughly $100–300 — and at this carat weight in a brilliant cut, E color is visually indistinguishable from D in the vast majority of settings. E-IF is the smarter buy unless you specifically want "D" on the certificate.

