## Which Clarity Grade Should You Buy for a Pear Cut Diamond?

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Clarity Grade</th><th>Eye-Clean in Pear?</th><th>Buy It?</th><th>Farzana's Verdict</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>FL/IF</strong></td><td>100%</td><td>Lab only, skip for natural</td><td>In natural diamonds the FL/IF premium is enormous (see the $93,910–$119,400 stones above) for an invisible distinction. In lab-grown, the price difference is small enough that IF is worth taking.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>VVS1/VVS2</strong></td><td>100%</td><td>Yes, if priced well</td><td>Strong middle-ground choice, particularly useful if an inclusion-free zone near the point matters to you specifically.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>VS1</strong></td><td>100%</td><td><strong>Yes — recommended floor</strong></td><td>The brilliant facet pattern hides inclusions well across most of the stone. VS1 is the safer floor specifically because of the point — you want margin there.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>VS2</strong></td><td>85–90%, lower near the point</td><td>Yes, with point-specific video audit</td><td>Acceptable everywhere except directly at or near the point, where any visible inclusion both shows more and coincides with the structurally weakest part of the stone.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>SI1</strong></td><td>65–75%, point-dependent</td><td>Caution — mandatory point check</td><td>Possible to find eye-clean SI1 pears, but you must specifically verify no inclusion sits at or near the tip before buying.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>SI2</strong></td><td>Variable, often visible</td><td>Avoid</td><td>Too much risk of visible inclusions, especially compounded by point placement concerns.</td></tr></tbody></table>

The point-specific caution here is what differentiates pear from oval or round on clarity selection. For more on how inclusion type and placement interact with brilliant-cut shapes generally, see our **[diamond clarity chart](https://diamondcritics.com/diamond-clarity-chart/)** and **[VS1 clarity guide](https://diamondcritics.com/vs1-clarity-diamonds/)**.

## Which Color Grade Should You Buy for a Pear Cut Diamond?

Pear cuts show color slightly more readily at the point and the corners than a round brilliant does, because the elongated facet structure concentrates color toward the tips of the stone. This makes pear marginally more color-sensitive than round or cushion, though far less sensitive than a step-cut shape like emerald.

For natural pear diamonds, G or H color in white gold or platinum is the practical sweet spot based on the price data above — the jump from G to D color routinely adds $500–$11,000+ depending on carat weight, for a distinction that's difficult to detect in a brilliant-cut shape even with the slightly increased color concentration at the tips. A white diamond pear in G or H color set in platinum or 14K white gold is visually indistinguishable from a D-color stone at conversational distance.

For lab-grown pear, E color offers nearly identical value to D at a small discount.

If you're set on yellow gold, step down to H or I color — yellow gold's warm tone will mask any residual warmth in the stone itself, letting you redirect budget toward carat weight. Full breakdown at our **[diamond color scale](https://diamondcritics.com/diamond-color-scale/)** guide.

## Pear vs. Other Shapes: How Does It Compare?

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Comparison</th><th>Key Difference</th><th>Farzana's Take</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Pear vs. Round</strong></td><td>Pear is 10–20% cheaper, asymmetrical, has a vulnerable point</td><td>Round wins on safety and resale familiarity; pear wins on distinctiveness and elongation. See our <a href="https://diamondcritics.com/">round cut guide</a> for the full comparison baseline.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Pear vs. Oval</strong></td><td>Oval has no vulnerable point; pear has a more dramatic, distinctive silhouette</td><td>If you want elongation with zero structural concerns, oval is the safer pick. If you want a genuinely unique, more dramatic shape and are willing to manage point protection, pear delivers something oval can't. See our <a href="https://diamondcritics.com/oval-cut-diamond/">oval cut guide</a>.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Pear vs. Marquise</strong></td><td>Marquise has two points (both ends), pear has only one</td><td>Marquise is more dramatic and more fragile — two vulnerable points instead of one. Pear is the more wearable middle ground between marquise's drama and oval's safety.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Pear vs. Cushion</strong></td><td>Cushion is symmetrical with rounded corners, pear is asymmetrical with one point</td><td>Cushion is the safer, more classic choice for everyday durability. Pear is the choice for buyers specifically seeking an elongated, teardrop silhouette. See our <a href="https://diamondcritics.com/cushion-cut-diamond/">cushion cut guide</a>.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Pear vs. Emerald</strong></td><td>Pear is a brilliant cut (sparkle), emerald is a step cut (flash)</td><td>Completely different optical personalities — pear scintillates, emerald reflects in broad planes. Choose based on which look you actually prefer, not price. See our <a href="https://diamondcritics.com/emerald-cut-diamond/">emerald cut guide</a>.</td></tr></tbody></table>

