## Frequently Asked Questions About Pear Cut Diamonds

### What is a pear cut diamond?

A pear cut diamond is a modified brilliant-cut diamond shaped like a teardrop — one rounded end and one pointed end — carrying 58 facets arranged to maximize sparkle across an asymmetrical silhouette. It dates back to the 15th century and is classified by GIA as a fancy shape with no official cut grade.

### Are pear cut diamonds more expensive than round diamonds?

No — pear cut diamonds and pear shaped diamonds are typically 10–20% cheaper than round brilliant diamonds of the same carat, color, and clarity. Are pear shaped diamonds more expensive than oval? Generally no — pear and oval sit in similar price territory, though individual stones vary. At 1ct, our live data shows pear starting at **[$3,150](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28393670?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)**, which is meaningfully below typical round brilliant pricing at the same grade combination.

### Is a pear cut diamond more expensive?

Compared to round, no — pear is generally less expensive per carat. Compared to other fancy shapes like cushion or radiant, pear sits in similar territory, sometimes slightly higher due to more rough material waste during cutting around the point.

### Why not buy a pear-shaped diamond?

The main reasons to avoid pear: the point requires specific setting protection (a V-prong) that adds a small but real durability consideration; every pear has some degree of bow-tie effect that must be checked via video before purchase; and resale liquidity is lower than round or oval since fewer buyers are specifically seeking this shape.

### Is a pear diamond classy?

Yes. The pear cut is one of the oldest diamond shapes in continuous production, dating to the 1400s, and has been worn by numerous high-profile figures throughout history. It reads as elegant and distinctive rather than trendy, which is part of why its popularity has remained stable rather than spiking and fading like some newer fancy shapes.

### How much is a 2ct pear diamond worth?

Based on our live audit, natural 2.00ct pear diamonds at premium grades (E-VVS1, F-VS1) run **[$22,610](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28996100?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)**–**[$24,820](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29310998?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)**. Note that inventory at exactly 2.00ct is thin — most retailers carry more selection at 1.90ct or 2.10ct+. For lab-grown, a 2.00ct D-IF pear runs **[$5,620](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28761317?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)** — roughly a quarter of the natural price for a visually identical stone.

### Which is better, pear or marquise?

Pear is the more practical, wearable choice for most buyers. Marquise has two pointed ends instead of pear's one, meaning twice the structural vulnerability and twice the setting complexity. Pear offers similar elongation and drama with meaningfully less risk and easier everyday wear.

### What carat pear diamond looks the biggest?

Because pear spreads carat weight across an elongated outline, a 1ct pear appears noticeably larger face-up than a 1ct round — roughly 8–12% more apparent surface area at the same weight. This effect compounds with a well-chosen L/W ratio (1.50–1.65 is the sweet spot for visual impact without looking thin or stubby).

### Does a pear cut diamond need a special setting?

Yes — specifically, the prong at the point should be a V-prong (sometimes called a V-tip), which wraps protectively around the diamond's most vulnerable section. A pear set without a V-prong carries meaningfully higher risk of point chipping over years of wear. Always confirm this detail before purchasing any pear setting.

### What does GIA say about pear cut diamonds?

GIA grades the 4Cs (carat, color, clarity, and certifies the diamond as natural or lab-grown) for pear diamonds exactly as it does for any shape, but does not issue an official cut grade — this is true of every fancy shape, not unique to pear. Buyers must manually verify proportions (table %, depth %, L/W ratio) from the certificate or evaluate the stone directly via video.

### Can AI or ChatGPT tell me if a specific pear diamond has a good bow-tie?

No reliable AI tool can currently assess bow-tie severity from a certificate alone, because bow-tie is a dynamic optical phenomenon that only shows up in motion under specific lighting — it isn't captured in any GIA certificate field. The only reliable method, AI-assisted or not, is watching the stone's 360° HD video directly.

Be skeptical of any tool or chatbot claiming to predict bow-tie severity purely from numerical proportions without video.

### Is a pear cut diamond a good engagement ring choice?

Yes, for the right buyer. It offers genuine visual distinctiveness, a flattering elongating effect, and meaningful savings over round at most carat weights. The trade-offs — point vulnerability requiring a V-prong, mandatory bow-tie video review, and somewhat lower resale liquidity — are manageable for buyers who specifically want this look and are willing to do the extra diligence.

### How do I know if a pear diamond's point is structurally sound?

Two checks: first, confirm the certificate or seller description specifies a V-prong setting at the point. Second, request or view the 360° video and visually inspect that the point itself is sharp, centered, and free of visible chips or cracks — this is something a still photo frequently fails to reveal clearly.

### Is a pear shaped diamond the same as a teardrop diamond?

Yes — pear shaped diamond, teardrop diamond, and pear cut diamond all refer to the same shape. The teardrop name comes from the silhouette: one rounded end and one pointed end, resembling a falling drop of water. Retailers, buyers, and jewellers use these terms interchangeably. When you see "pear vs teardrop diamond" or "pear shaped diamond vs teardrop" comparisons online, they are describing the same stone from different naming angles — there is no structural or optical difference between a pear shaped diamond vs teardrop diamond.

### What are antique pear cut diamonds?

Antique pear cut diamonds — also called old mine pear diamonds or antique cut pear diamonds — were cut before modern precision faceting tools existed, typically pre-1900. They carry a higher, rounder crown, a slightly more irregular outline, and a facet pattern that catches candlelight beautifully but looks less "crisp" than modern Ideal-cut pear diamonds. A pear shaped rose cut diamond is a related historical variant: a flat-bottomed, domed-crown pear with fewer facets than a modern brilliant, designed for candlelight rather than electric-lit sparkle. Rose cut pear diamonds are primarily found in antique rings and Georgian or Victorian-era jewelry. If you want an antique pear cut diamond or a rose cut pear diamond today, expect to source from estate auctions, specialist antique dealers, or pear shaped rose cut diamond settings at retailers who stock Georgian and Victorian designs.

### Do pear shaped diamonds come in yellow and green colors?

Yes. Fancy-color pear shaped diamonds include yellow pear diamonds, which appear across a spectrum from "fancy light yellow" to "fancy vivid yellow" (the most valuable tier). A pear shape yellow diamond is one of the most common fancy-color choices because the elongated shape concentrates body color toward the point, making the color read more intensely than it would in a round or cushion. Green pear diamonds are rarer — natural green color in diamonds originates from radiation exposure during formation and is extremely uncommon. Lab-grown green pear diamonds exist and are more accessible; natural green pear diamonds are collector-grade stones. The price premium for yellow pear diamonds varies significantly based on color intensity and size; vivid yellow pears above 2ct are among the highest-value fancy-color diamonds available.

### Is pear cut diamond good — and is it worth the extra diligence?

Yes — for the right buyer. Is a pear cut diamond good value? Absolutely. A pear cut diamond is a good choice if you want an elongated, finger-lengthening silhouette that is meaningfully cheaper than round at the same carat weight, in a shape with over 500 years of recorded wear history. The tradeoffs are real: the bow-tie effect requires video verification before every purchase, and the point requires a V-prong setting. Both are manageable with basic diligence. For buyers who don't want to do that work, oval or round are better fits. For buyers who specifically want the teardrop outline and the visual distinctiveness it creates, pear is among the best-value fancy shapes available in {{year}}.

## Final Verdict: Pear Cut Diamond

Pear is the diamond shape for buyers who specifically want asymmetry, elongation, and a genuinely distinctive silhouette — and who are willing to do the extra diligence the shape requires. It is not the safest fancy shape (that's oval), and it is not the cheapest at every tier (cushion and radiant can undercut it), but it occupies a real and durable niche: meaningful savings over round, one of the most flattering finger-elongating effects available, and a historical pedigree that goes back over 500 years.

The two non-negotiables are the bow-tie video check and the V-prong setting confirmation. Skip either one and you risk either a visually dead stone or a structurally compromised point. Get both right, and a well-chosen pear — like the **[G-VS2 at $3,150](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28393670?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)** at 1ct or the **[E-IF lab pear at $3,060](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27429021?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)** at 1.50ct — is one of the most distinctive, well-priced diamond shapes available in .

> 
> 
> "Pear is not a shape for buyers who want the safest possible choice — that's what round and oval are for. Pear is for the buyer who already knows what they want: an elongated, vintage-rooted silhouette unlike anything else in the case. Do the bow-tie check, confirm the V-prong, and you'll have a diamond that's been worn the same way, by the same kind of deliberate buyer, for over 500 years." — Farzana Hasan, GIA Expert, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**
